I89. Preference for commercial items

I11(a) T4Relationship of Provisions of Law to Procurement of Commercial Items._

I12(1) T4This divisionK._Unless otherwise specifically provided, all other provisions in this division also apply to the procurement of commercial items.

I12(2) T4Laws listed in federal acquisition regulationK._A contract for the procurement of a commercial item entered into by the head of an executive agency is not subject to a law properly listed in the Federal Acquisition Regulation pursuant to section 1906 of this title.

Q04

I11(b) T4PreferenceK._The head of each executive agency shall ensure that, to the maximum extent practicable_

I12(1) requirements of the executive agency with respect to a procurement of supplies or services are stated in terms of_

I13(A) functions to be performed;

I13(B) performance required; or

I13(C) essential physical characteristics;

Q04

I12(2) those requirements are defined so that commercial items or, to the extent that commercial items suitable to meet the executive agency's needs are not available, nondevelopmental items other than commercial items may be procured to fulfill those requirements; and

I12(3) offerors of commercial items and nondevelopmental items other than commercial items are provided an opportunity to compete in any procurement to fill those requirements.

Q04

I11(c) T4ImplementationK._The head of each executive agency shall ensure that procurement officials in that executive agency, to the maximum extent practicable_

I12(1) acquire commercial items or nondevelopmental items other than commercial items to meet the needs of the executive agency;

I12(2) require that prime contractors and subcontractors at all levels under contracts of the executive agency incorporate commercial items or nondevelopmental items other than commercial items as components of items supplied to the executive agency;

I12(3) modify requirements in appropriate cases to ensure that the requirements can be met by commercial items or, to the extent that commercial items suitable to meet the executive agency's needs are not available, nondevelopmental items other than commercial items;

I12(4) state specifications in terms that enable and encourage bidders and offerors to supply commercial items or, to the extent that commercial items suitable to meet the executive agency's needs are not available, nondevelopmental items other than commercial items in response to the executive agency solicitations;

I12(5) revise the executive agency's procurement policies, practices, and procedures not required by law to reduce any impediments in those policies, practices, and procedures to the acquisition of commercial items; and

I12(6) require training of appropriate personnel in the acquisition of commercial items.

Q04

I11(d) T4Market Research._

I12(1) T4When to be usedK._The head of an executive agency shall conduct market research appropriate to the circumstances_

I13(A) before developing new specifications for a procurement by that executive agency; and

I13(B) before soliciting bids or proposals for a contract in excess of the simplified acquisition threshold.

Q04

I12(2) T4Use of resultsK._The head of an executive agency shall use the results of market research to determine whether commercial items or, to the extent that commercial items suitable to meet the executive agency's needs are not available, nondevelopmental items other than commercial items are available that_

I13(A) meet the executive agency's requirements;

I13(B) could be modified to meet the executive agency's requirements; or

I13(C) could meet the executive agency's requirements if those requirements were modified to a reasonable extent.

Q04

I12(3) T4Only minimum information required to be submittedK._In conducting market research, the head of an executive agency should not require potential sources to submit more than the minimum information that is necessary to make the determinations required in paragraph (2).

Q04

I11(e) T4Regulations._

I12(1) T4In generalK._The Federal Acquisition Regulation shall provide regulations to implement this section, sections 102, 103, 105, and 110 of this title, and chapter 140 of title 10.

I12(2) T4Contract clauses._

I13(A) T4DefinitionK._In this paragraph, the term ``subcontract'' includes a transfer of commercial items between divisions, subsidiaries, or affiliates of a contractor or subcontractor.

I13(B) T4List of clauses to be includedK._The regulations prescribed under paragraph (1) shall contain a list of contract clauses to be included in contracts for the acquisition of commercial end items. To the maximum extent practicable, the list shall include only those contract clauses that are_

I14(i) required to implement provisions of law or executive orders applicable to acquisitions of commercial items or commercial components; or

I14(ii) determined to be consistent with standard commercial practice.

Q04

I13(C) T4Requirements of prime contractorK._The regulations shall provide that the Federal Government shall not require a prime contractor to apply to any of its divisions, subsidiaries, affiliates, subcontractors, or suppliers that are furnishing commercial items any contract clause except those that are_

I14(i) required to implement provisions of law or executive orders applicable to subcontractors furnishing commercial items or commercial components; or

I14(ii) determined to be consistent with standard commercial practice.

Q04

I13(D) T4Clauses that may be used in a contractK._To the maximum extent practicable, only the contract clauses listed pursuant to subparagraph (B) may be used in a contract, and only the contract clauses referred to in subparagraph (C) may be required to be used in a subcontract, for the acquisition of commercial items or commercial components by or for an executive agency.

I13(E) T4Waiver of contract clausesK._The Federal Acquisition Regulation shall provide standards and procedures for waiving the use of contract clauses required pursuant to subparagraph (B), other than those required by law, including standards for determining the cases in which a waiver is appropriate.

Q04

I12(3) T4Market acceptance._

I13(A) T4Requirement of offerorsK._The Federal Acquisition Regulation shall provide that under appropriate conditions the head of an executive agency may require offerors to demonstrate that the items offered_

I14(i) have achieved commercial market acceptance or been satisfactorily supplied to an executive agency under current or recent contracts for the same or similar requirements; and

I14(ii) otherwise meet the item description, specifications, or other criteria prescribed in the public notice and solicitation relating to the contract.

Q04

I13(B) T4Regulation to provide guidance on criteriaK._The Federal Acquisition Regulation shall provide guidance to ensure that the criteria for determining commercial market acceptance include the consideration of_

I14(i) the minimum needs of the executive agency concerned; and

I14(ii) the entire relevant commercial market, including small businesses.

Q04

I12(4) T4Provisions relating to types of contracts._

I13(A) T4Types of contracts that may be usedK._The Federal Acquisition Regulation shall include, for acquisitions of commercial items_

I14(i) a requirement that firm, fixed price contracts or fixed price with economic price adjustment contracts be used to the maximum extent practicable;

I14(ii) a prohibition on use of cost type contracts; and

I14(iii) subject to subparagraph (B), authority for use of a time-and-materials or labor-hour contract for the procurement of commercial services that are commonly sold to the general public through those contracts and are purchased by the procuring agency on a competitive basis.

Q04

I13(B) T4When time-and-materials or labor-hour contract may be usedK._A time-and-materials or labor-hour contract may be used pursuant to the authority referred to in subparagraph (A)(iii)_

I14(i) only for a procurement of commercial services in a category of commercial services described in subparagraph (C); and

I14(ii) only if the contracting officer for the procurement_

I16(I) executes a determination and findings that no other contract type is suitable;

I16(II) includes in the contract a ceiling price that the contractor exceeds at its own risk; and

I16(III) authorizes a subsequent change in the ceiling price only on a determination, documented in the contract file, that it is in the best interest of the procuring agency to change the ceiling price.

Q04

I13(C) T4Categories of commercial servicesK._The categories of commercial services referred to in subparagraph (B) are as follows:

I14(i) Commercial services procured for support of a commercial item, as described in section 103(5) of this title.

I14(ii) Any other category of commercial services that the Administrator for Federal Procurement Policy designates in the Federal Acquisition Regulation for the purposes of this subparagraph on the basis that_

I16(I) the commercial services in the category are of a type of commercial services that are commonly sold to the general public through use of time-and-materials or labor-hour contracts; and

I16(II) it would be in the best interests of the Federal Government to authorize use of time-and-materials or labor-hour contracts for purchases of the commercial services in the category.

Q04

I12(5) T4Contract quality requirementsK._Regulations prescribed under paragraph (1) shall include provisions that_

I13(A) allow, to the maximum extent practicable, a contractor under a commercial items acquisition to use the existing quality assurance system of the contractor as a substitute for compliance with an otherwise applicable requirement for the Federal Government to inspect or test the commercial items before the contractor's tender of those items for acceptance by the Federal Government;

I13(B) require that, to the maximum extent practicable, the executive agency take advantage of warranties (including extended warranties) offered by offerors of commercial items and use those warranties for the repair and replacement of commercial items; and

I13(C) set forth guidance regarding the use of past performance of commercial items and sources as a factor in contract award decisions.

